# Improved Literature Review

Recent research suggests that artificial intelligence has the potential to enhance education through personalized learning, adaptive assessments, automated grading, and intelligent tutoring systems. Multiple studies report improvements in learning efficiency and teacher productivity when AI is implemented appropriately.

However, researchers also identify significant challenges. Common concerns include data privacy, algorithmic bias, unequal access to technology, academic integrity, and excessive dependence on AI tools. Some studies argue that educational outcomes depend heavily on teacher training, institutional support, and responsible implementation rather than AI alone.

Current literature generally agrees that AI can improve educational outcomes when used to support—not replace—educators. However, further research is needed to examine long-term learning outcomes, ethical governance, and equitable access across different educational environments.

---

# Reflection

## What I Learned

A literature review is more than a collection of summaries. It should synthesize evidence, compare findings across studies, identify disagreements, and highlight areas requiring further research.

---

## What I'd Do Differently

Evaluate a larger number of peer-reviewed studies and explicitly discuss where research findings agree, conflict, or remain inconclusive.

